<H3> <TI>   Tension Between Crimean, Ukrainian Authorities Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tension Between Crimean, Ukrainian Authorities Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704131194 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1100 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0704131194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Novosti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] It appears that the battle between the authorities 
of Ukraine and Crimea has worsened. Crimean President Yuriy 
Meshkov says the situation that has taken shape on the peninsula 
is due to provocations by the powers that be in Ukraine. 
  [Correspondent Vladimir Plotnikov] Kravchuk's decree 
appointing a representative of the Ukrainian president in Crimea 
has aroused particular opposition. The leadership of Crimea's 
republican movement, Russian Society, [Russkoye Obshchestvo] 
today called on citizens to rally in support of the Crimean 
president. 
  [Begin Crimean President Meshkov recording] [Words 
indistinct] that Ukraine's current leadership is the most 
dangerous, from the point of view of maintaining peace and calm 
in Europe. This leadership has relied on, and unfortunately 
continues to rely on, extreme nationalist forces in Ukraine and 
can only act within a framework designed by the nationalists. 
[end recording] 
  [Plotnikov] It may be by chance, but the war of decrees 
broke 
out on the eve of the second round of elections to the Ukrainian 
and Crimean parliaments. It might be expected that this war 
will help consolidate Meshkov's supporters. Even the autonomous 
republic's Supreme Soviet, with its current composition and 
history of total subservience to Kiev, has spoken against the 
appointment of a representative for Kravchuk in Crimea. [Video 
shows Meshkov talking to journalists and a rally in Crimea] 

</TEXT>

