<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poltoranin Calls For Reformist `Political Group' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poltoranin Calls For Reformist `Political Group' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0204104494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0952 GMT 2 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0204104494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 2 KYODO -- A senior aide to Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin said Saturday [2 April] Russian 
reformist politicians will band to create a new political group 
intent on reinvigorating moves toward democracy. 
  Mikhail Poltoranin, chairman of the Intelligence Policy 
Committee of the State Duma, said in an interview with Kyodo 
News Service in Tokyo that the new group will help prevent 
Russian democratic forces from being splintered. 
  The State Duma is the 450-member lower house of the Russian 
parliament. 
  The group will consist of Poltoranin, former Deputy Prime 
Minister Yegor Gaydar, former State Secretary Gennadiy Burbulis 
and other reformist politicians, he said. 
  The establishment of the new group will be pushed to help 
accomplish Yeltsin's recent proposal to have the Russian 
parliament adopt a declaration committing all political forces 
to seek to achieve national reconciliation, he said. 
  Poltoranin said he is convinced that Yeltsin will agree to 
join the new group, saying the president is aware that he has 
drawn his political strength chiefly from reformist politicians. 
  "The president is aware that his support base comes from 
reformists and he would end up losing his power if he lost their 
support," he said. 
  Poltoranin dismissed as false propaganda the rumors that the 
health of Yeltsin has deteriorated to a level so bad as to make 
it difficult for him to engage in his presidential duties. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

