<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Debates Continue on Abkhaz Peace Deal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Debates Continue on Abkhaz Peace Deal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0604154494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1137 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0604154494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Georgian parliament continued debate on the 
regional peace agreement signed in Moscow on Monday. Debates on 
the same topic the day before had yielded no results. 
  Opposition members have failed to offer any alternative to 
the peace deal, our correspondent reports. 
  At the same time, one opposition member Boris Kakubava has 
made an abortive attempt to bring a motion of no-confidence in 
Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze. 
  In an emotional address to the house, head of the interim 
committee for the state of emergency Jaba Ioseliani called the 
opposition's bluff: "What exactly do you want? If you want 
war, you must say so. But if you want peace, this can be 
achieved by moving step by step, including agreements similar to 
that signed in Moscow." 

</TEXT>

