<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shakhray Urges More Time for Signing Civil Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shakhray Urges More Time for Signing Civil Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK0504101094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 5 Apr 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> MK0504101094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Yevgeniy Krasnikov report under the "In Brief" rubric: </F>
"Shakhray Satisfied With Memorandum on Accord"] 
  [Text] Sergey Shakhray has told your NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA 
correspondent that he received the draft memorandum on civil 
accord drawn up by the presidential administration (during the 
drafting Shakhray himself supervised the work of a section that 
drew up the memorandum's provisions on interethnic and 
inter-regional relations). Shakhray said that he was completely 
satisfied with "the high quality of the document," but he had a 
number of proposals to make regarding the procedure of adopting 
it. Shakhray believes that the ratification of the document 
should not be rushed and that "it would be better to work on it 
for a month or two," than to have it signed by representatives 
of parties representing the same political spectrum. In 
Shakhray's view, "this slowness" in drawing up the document will 
enable, say, Anatoliy Lukyanov and his allies, "who are 
preparing their own draft document on civil accord," to join it. 
Shakhray thinks that the document should be passed to the State 
Duma, adopted by it as a law, and opened for new signatories. 
"Both Rybkin and Yeltsin ought to sign the memorandum not as 
citizens, but as statesmen," Shakhray said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-15236 </DOCNO>
