<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Amends Draft Agreement on Civic Peace </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Amends Draft Agreement on Civic Peace </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0604174494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1411 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0604174494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] As Interfax reported earlier, on Tuesday evening 
President Yeltsin sent copies of the draft agreement on civic 
peace to the potential signatories. 
  The only difference between that draft and the one prepared 
earlier was the absence of the provision on measures to increase 
wages in accordance with inflation and to ensure their timely 
payment, to check the rise in prices on staple food stuffs, to 
create jobs and to help the regions where the danger of 
unemployment is the greatest. 
  Head of the president's experts Aleksandr Livshyts told 
Interfax on Wednesday that such an amendment had been motivated 
by the need to scrupulously work out this provision. He said 
that the amendment did not mean Yeltsin denied the importance of 
those measures. He said, however, that the initial variant 
sounded rather abstract because it did not say who was 
responsible for implementing them. Livshyts believes that this 
drawback will be done away with in the final draft. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

