<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ilyushenko To Perform Duties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ilyushenko To Perform Duties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0604175194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1411 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0604175194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] "Even if the Council of the Federation disagrees 
with the resignation of Aleksey Kazannik from the post of 
Prosecutor General, his duties will be performed by Aleksey 
Ilyushenko appointed to the post by President Yeltsin." This is 
the opinion of the official presidential representative in the 
Federal Assembly, the prominent lawyer Aleksandr Yakovlev. 
  On Wednesday he told Interfax that under the constitution 
the 
Council of the Federation appoints and dismisses the Prosecutor 
General but only candidates proposed by the president. 
Therefore, in Yakovlev's opinion, "common sense prompts that 
the council itself does not have the right to appoint anyone 
acting Prosecutor General, this remains the prerogative of the 
president." 
  Yakovlev recalled that Kazannik resigned of his own free 
will, not as a result of "any unlawful moves by the leadership, 
in this case the president." "Therefore in any case the duties 
of the Prosecutor General will be performed by the person 
appointed by the president," Yakovlev said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

