<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Industry Employee Arrested as Spy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Industry Employee Arrested as Spy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0604133494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1249 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0604133494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoliy Yurkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 6 TASS -- Russian counterintelligence 
officers have arrested a defence industry employee who tried to 
trade state secrets to foreigners, said Boris Miroshnikov, 
deputy head of the counterintelligence operations department of 
the Russian Counterintelligence Service. 
  In an interview with ITAR-TASS on Wednesday, Miroshnikov 
said 
that the number of such cases has grown lately. People offering 
"spy service" to foreigners justify their behaviour by their 
"desire to be paid according to their intellect." 
  Miroshnikov expressed concern about the fact that foreign 
intelligence services have stepped up their activity in Russia 
under the cover of various foundations and joint ventures. 
Russian business people and industrialists seeking credits or 
equipment for their businesses sometimes sell secrets to foreign 
emissaries or those who act legally and openly under the cover 
of firms and companies, he said. 
  Taking advantage of Russia's weakened administrative and 
legal system, foreign spies penetrate all spheres of activity. 
Their neutralisation forces Russia's counterintelligence to 
look for new ways and methods of intelligence warfare and to 
conduct systematic analytical work. 
  The situation is compounded by the fact that foreign states 
have set up intelligence centres in some republics of the former 
Soviet Union and, in fact, have taken over the local 
intelligence services. They wage active intelligence work 
against Russia, using politically unstable areas, trouble spots, 
the Islamic factor and aggressive nationalism, Miroshnikov 
concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

