<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Media Arbitration Court Warns Opposition Newspaper </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Media Arbitration Court Warns Opposition Newspaper </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0604162894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1318 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0604162894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Ivanova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 6 TASS -- The Russian Mass Media 
Arbitration Court warned a hard-line opposition newspaper it may 
be closed if it continues to publish speculative anti-Yeltsin 
articles. 
  The court ruled that the publication of extracts from a 
novel 
"Mysteries of Kremlin" by former Soviet mp Iona Andronov in the 
newspaper "ZAVTRA" (TOMORROW), the successor to the notorious 
"DEN", presented a violation of "the law on the press". 
  The court stated that in accordance with the law the 
government is entitled to issue a corresponding officiial 
warning to the newspaper. Two such warnings within one year are 
enough to close the periodical. 
  The court stated that the publication was "based on absurd 
conjectures" and qualified it as aimed to "destabilize the 
situation in Russia and bar the signing of the memorandum on 
civic peace". 
  The published extracts from the novel by an ardent Yeltsin's 
foe alongside with bitter criticism against the Russian 
president, concentrated on the most delicate theme of the 
present political situation -- the state of health of the 
Russian number one. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

