<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Industry Chief on Plans To Revive Exports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Industry Chief on Plans To Revive Exports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK0504093094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 5 Apr 94 
p 4 </F>

<F P=103> MK0504093094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [RIA report under the "In Brief" rubric: "Russian Arms </F>
Export Up"] 
  [Text] The export of Russian arms and military hardware in 
1993 was up 11.7 percent, standing at $2.15 billion. 
Interestingly, the share of products intended for export 
amounted to as little as 5.2 percent of the arms manufactured. 
This was announced by Viktor Glukhikh, chairman of the Russian 
State Committee on the Defense Industry. He admitted that the 
number of arms importing countries had fallen to 26, that is to 
half of what it was at the time of the former USSR in 1990. 
Importantly, Russia has virtually lost an arms market in the 
Baltics, where arms now come from Israel. According to him, 
Moldavia [Moldova] is increasingly orienting itself in its 
imports policy toward Romania, while arms suppliers in China, 
Iran, and Turkey are actively working in the newly formed states 
of Central Asia. 
  Still, Glukhikh thinks that the CIS market should be a 
priority for Russia. There is a considerable quantity of 
weapons there created on the basis of the former Soviet 
standards and arms systems which are being produced in Russia. 
To boost arms exports, the head of the State Committee on the 
Defense Industry thinks, one should arrange for supplies of 
spare parts for military hardware, servicing, repairs, and 
modernization of armaments delivered. These problems will be 
tackled as a package by the recently created "Rosvooruzheniye" 
state company. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

