<H3> <TI>   Servicemen Threatened With Loss of Perks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Servicemen Threatened With Loss of Perks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK0704122094 Moscow MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS in Russian 7 Apr 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> MK0704122094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report under the "Hold the Front Page!" </F>
rubric: "They Beat Our Army on All Fronts"] 
  [Text] The heads of interested ministries have submitted 
their proposals for the next Council of Ministers session, which 
will look at benefits for servicemen. 
  To all appearances, officers and retired servicemen of the 
armed forces will have to part with many benefits. In his 
letter to Chernomyrdin, Deputy Finance Minister Astakhov 
proposes that servicemen be deprived of free medical service 
(that is to say, the network of military outpatient hospitals 
should be closed down), and that compensation for treatment at 
sanatoriums and health resorts and transport fares be abolished. 
At the same time, Astakhov proposes that staffers of the 
Russian Federation Ministry of Internal Affairs entitled to 
retirement pensions but continuing to serve should receive 
additionally an average of 75,000 rubles each. 
  Deputy Minister of Economy Mikhaylov, responding to the same 
request, thinks that benefits for servicemen cannot be available 
in 1994, and he suggests that federal budget possibilities be 
studied once again. Deputy Social Protection Minister Kisilev 
writes to Chernomyrdin that their agency is against the 
mandatory state insurance of servicemen's property, and for 
abolishing reduced prices in trade outlets for military 
personnel. 
  The Finance Ministry also insists that even if servicemen 
are 
to keep their benefits, it should only be done from the Defense 
Ministry's own budget -- which has been considerably reduced 
through the efforts of this same Finance Ministry. 

</TEXT>

