<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Stations Face `Stoppages' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Stations Face `Stoppages' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0504135194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1305 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0504135194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Marina Barinova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 5 TASS -- All Russian nuclear power 
stations now face stoppages. Because of various faults nuclear 
reactors at many of them do not operate to full capacity. In 
addition to technical reasons, the work of nine Russian nuclear 
power stations is affected by huge indebtedness to them by 
consumers. It amounts now to over 600 billion roubles. 
Observers believe this urges operators to protest actions such 
as the picketing of the government building conducted today. 
Because of the lack of funds, nuclear fuel cannot be bought. 
Prophylactic work cannot be done on time. Planned recharging 
of reactors with fuel is skipped. So nuclear power plants in 
Russia may turn out of energy producers into major energy 
consumers. 
  Social tension is heightening among the personnel of nuclear 
power plants. Wages have not been paid to them for three of 
four months. Nuclear power plant operators have to resort to 
extreme measures. Five operators of the Kursk nuclear power 
station were recently fasting in protest against non-payment of 
wages. Despite the government decision to conclude collective 
agreements with workers in nuclear power, such an agreement was 
concluded with the personnel of only one of the nine stations, 
the Beloyarsk nuclear power plant. 
  The coordination council for joint actions formed by trade 
unions of nuclear power sent an address to the Russian 
president, government and parliament. The address pointed to 
the need to stabilise the financial situation in the region. 
  So far all Russian nuclear power stations have to work in a 
regime on strict economy. Because of this their output dropped 
by half. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

