<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yarov on Calls for Protecting Poor People </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yarov on Calls for Protecting Poor People </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0604170294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1550 
GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0604170294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Liliya Kuznetsova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 6 Apr -- To stop the increase in the number 
of people in Russia who find themselves beyond the poverty line 
-- this is the main objective of the state social policy in 
1994. Yuriy Yarov, deputy chairman of the Russian Government, 
said this today at a meeting between heads of ministries and 
services of the social bloc and journalists. 
  In his opinion, the fight against hyperinflation and social 
stabilization in society should not be set against each other; 
one should not put financial interests above those common to all 
people, while at the same time one should not forget that 
people's lives cannot be improved without improving the economy 
and reducing inflationary processes. 
  The social policy, Yuriy Yarov said, is the first to be 
affected by a fall in production. Reduced budget revenues have 
resulted in a situation whereby the Finance Ministry's debt to 
the social sphere in 1993 amounted to 228 billion rubles. In 
addition, although last year's debts are being paid off, 
non-payments for the first quarter of 1994 are growing: as of 
today the debt amounts to 500 billion rubles. 
  At the same time, the deputy chairman of the Russian 
Government said that only 12.4 trillion rubles have been 
allocated to resolving all social problems, which is 9.5 percent 
of the budget. In his view, at least 15 per cent of the federal 
budget's assets are necessary just to resolve the most painful 
problems in the sphere. 

</TEXT>

