<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Predicts Sharp Rise in Jobless this Year </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Predicts Sharp Rise in Jobless this Year </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0604183594 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1600 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0604183594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Video report by correspondent R. Safronov; from the "Vesti" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] A number of ministers in charge of social issues, 
led by Yuriy Yarov, deputy chairman of the government, held a 
news conference today. They revealed some very interesting 
facts. For example, Labor Minister Gennadiy Melikyan said that 
the number of people in Russia with incomes below the poverty 
line nearly halved in February. The reason for this is that 
people working in the public sector had a pay rise in that 
month, the child allowance was increased, and pensioners began 
receiving compensation for inflation. 
  However, the current year does not hold any bright prospects 
in store. According to Yuriy Prokofyev, head of the Federal 
Employment Service, the country today has 989,000 registered 
unemployed, which amounts to one percent of the able-bodied 
population. As for the real unemployment figure, currently 
estimated at about 4 million, it could reach 6.5 million by the 
end of the year, accounting for eight percent of the able-bodied 
population. To prevent this category of the population from 
sliding into extreme poverty, public works such as street 
cleaning are to be organized, which will be paid for from the 
federal budget. The 100 percent unemployed will receive an 
unemployment benefit and those who would like to change their 
profession will be offered retraining schemes, with grants 
higher than the unemployment benefit. 

</TEXT>

