<H3> <TI>   No. Ossetian Speaker on Talks With Ingush Leaders </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    No. Ossetian Speaker on Talks With Ingush Leaders </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0504122094 Moscow RIA in English 0915 GMT 5 Apr 949--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD0504122094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow RIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vladikavkaz, April 5, RIA -- The speaker of the 
North Ossetian parliament, Yuriy Biragov, said that the decision 
to hold a second round of talks between the leaders of Northern 
Ossetia and the Ingush Republic in Nalchik on April 3 was a 
major political success, capable of breaking the deadlock in the 
relations between the two conflicting republics within Russia. 
According to the Ossetian parliament leader, personal contacts 
between North Ossetia's President Akhsarbek Galazov and Ingush 
President Ruslan Aushev may have a positive role to play in 
bringing peace to the south of Russia. Mr. Biragov said that 
the Ossetian side would insist on two "fundamental" conditions, 
namely that the Ingush republic abandon all territorial claims 
to Northern Ossetia and declare illegal and unconstitutional any 
attempts to settle the conflict by force. 
  According to the provisional administration in the disputed 
regions of the two republics, its Armed Forces control the 
situation in the state-of-emergency zone and continue to take 
measures to restore law and order there. The confiscation of 
illegal weapons from the population continues. On Monday 
transport police officers and Russian Interior Ministry 
officials discovered two Uzi automatic pistols in a sleeper of 
the Baku-Kislovodsk train, but failed to identify and arrest 
their owners. The investigation of the case continues. 
  A total of 246 submachine-guns, 22 machine-guns, 62 rifles 
and 417 pistols have been confiscated since the imposition of 
the state of emergency in the region. 

</TEXT>

