<F P=101> Russia International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Agreement Initialed on 1994 Oil, Gas Imports From Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Agreement Initialed on 1994 Oil, Gas Imports From Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU3003173094 Prague CTK in English 1441 GMT 30 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU3003173094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, March 30 (CTK) -- An intergovernmental 
protocol on the mutual supply of goods in 1994 was initialed 
today in Moscow by the Russian Ministry for Internal Economic 
Relations [as received] and the Czech Trade and Industry 
Ministry. 
  Among other goods, the document calls for the purchase of 7 
million tons of Russian oil and 6.9 billion cubic meters of 
natural gas. 
  Both countries have agreed that instead of drawing up yearly 
protocols, medium or long-term agreements should be concluded in 
coming years, Deputy Trade and Industry Minister Vaclav Petricek 
said. 
  The Czech delegation in Moscow agreed to cooperate further 
on 
the construction of natural gas works on the basis of 1982 
agreements, according to which the Czech Republic should get 
Russian natural gas in return for Czech supplies and labor. 
  Petricek in Moscow also discussed the possibility of Czech 
participation in the modernization of the natural gas industry 
in Russia and in the construction of a new natural gasline from 
Russia to Germany via Belarus and Poland. Czech firms could 
help build the gasline on Russian and Belarussian territory. 
Further negotiations concerned the possibility of hooking the 
gasline up to the Czech Republic's natural gas distribution 
network. 

</TEXT>

