<H3> <TI>   Abishev, Japan's Kumagai Discuss Economic Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Abishev, Japan's Kumagai Discuss Economic Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704154794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1309 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704154794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS-KAZTAG] </F>
  [Text] Tokyo 7 April, TASS -- The Japanese Government will 
soon beging insuring businesses conducting foreign economic 
transactions with Kazakhstan, Japanese Minister of Foreign Trade 
and Industry Hiroshi Kumagai said. 
  The announcement was made during Kumagai's meeting with 
visiting Kazakh Vice-Prime Minister Syzdyk Abishev who is 
accompanying Kazakh President Nursultan Nazarbayev on his 
official visit to Japan. 
  The Japanese-Kazakh project to modernise the metallurgic 
plant in Karaganda will be the first to be insured by Japan. 
There are also plans to extend state insurance to a new oil 
pipeline to be built in Kazakhstan. However, this will become 
possible only if the Kazakh government provides firm guarantees 
of credit payments to Japanese companies. 
  Abishev called on Japan to double investments in the Kazakh 
economy, adding that the Republic has only three joint ventures 
with the participation of Japanese capital. Kumagai expressed 
the hope that Japanese companies will boost investments in 
Kazakhstan if it creates favourable conditions for foreign 
investors. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

