<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo, Almaty To Increase Trade Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo, Almaty To Increase Trade Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704175294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1501 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704175294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo 7 April, TASS-KAZTAG -- Japan and Kazakhstan 
are ready to pool efforts to implement Alma-Ata's initiative and 
convene a conference on interaction and confidence-building in 
Asia similar to the Conference on Security and Cooperation in 
Europe, Kazakhstan's President Nursultan Nazarbayev and Japan's 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa said during their talks in 
Tokyo on Thursday. 
  Their meeting was held in the official residence of the head 
of the Japanese Government. It covered a wide array of 
political and economic items. As concerns the situation in 
Central Asia, Kazakhstan's president noted that Kazakhstan, 
Uzbekistan and Turkmenistan have to pursue a tough domestic 
policy in order to avert the spread of conflicts similar to that 
in Tajikistan throughout the region. As regards the domestic 
situation in Kazakhstan, Nazarbayev described it as politically 
stable. 
  Nazarbayev called for expanding the scale of economic 
integration in Asia as a whole and asked Tokyo to come forth 
with an initiative for the organisation of a common continental 
market. He stressed his country's readiness to serve as a base 
for Tokyo's penetration to Central Asian markets. 
  The president said that he is ready to give Japan preference 
in realizing major economic projects on the territory of his 
republic. For this purpose he suggested that Morihiro Hosokawa 
and himself set up a joint commission to prepare this important 
move. 
  The Japanese prime minister assured Alma-Ata of his 
invariable support for the transformations underway in 
Kazakhstan and said the projects named by Kazakhstan in the 
field of economic cooperation require a detailed study by 
Japan's leadership. 

</TEXT>

