Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Butrus-Ghali Holds News Conference on Visit, Departs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Butrus-Ghali Holds News Conference on Visit, Departs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0704141694 Minsk Radio Minsk Network in Belarusian 1200 
GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS0704141694 </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk Radio Minsk Network </F>
<F P=105>  Belarusian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Anatol Awcharenka] </F>
  [Excerpts] My visit to Minsk was extremely positive. This 
is how UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali assessed his 
meetings, negotiations, and talks [in Belarus], speaking at a 
conference with journalists at the National Press Center on 7 
April. In the course of a three-day visit, seven concrete 
issues were discussed at different levels with a Foreign 
Ministry delegation, at the Council of Ministers, and the 
Supreme Soviet. All of these issues are very important and 
urgent for Belarus, but the primary one is the problem stemming 
from the Chernobyl catastrophe. Mr. Butrus-Ghali arrived in our 
country to see what Chernobyl is, in reality. It is no secret 
that some countries are displaying weariness and losing interest 
in Chernobyl's problems. I am sure that the Belarusian side 
managed to provide the secretary general with convincing data 
contained in both the national report on Chernobyl and a special 
memorandum. These documents provide the most recent figures, 
the most current information. [passage omitted] 
  In the course of talks, both sides discussed measures to be 
taken to prevent the world community from reducing its 
involvement in alleviating the consequences of the Chernobyl 
accident. However, as was underlined at a news conference held 
by Belarusian Foreign Minister Pyotr Krawchanka, it will be 
impossible to fully eliminate the aftermath of the accident in 
this century. 
  The Belarusian side can also consider the general 
secretary's 
visit a success because it was attended by the director of the 
Economic Commission for European Affairs. His participation in 
the negotiations was not coincidental. In my opinion, his 
arrival in Belarus demonstrated to our government that the 
United Nations is ready to help Belarus survive its transitional 
phase and integrate into the world, or at least the European 
economy. Mr. Butrus-Ghali suggested that our Republic take part 
in peacekeeping operations in various regions of the world. The 
general secretary said: We would be very grateful to you if 
Belarus could provide at least a small contingent of blue 
helmets. He was told that under current legislation, only the 
Supreme Soviet can decree Belarusian servicemen's participation 
in operations outside the Republic. If the situation were to 
change, we could assist the United Nations in keeping peace 
around the world. 
  The UN and Belarusian delegations also discussed the 
situation of Belarusian ethnic minorities in Latvia and Estonia. 
Mr. Butrus-Ghali treats this problem very seriously, and that 
is why the two sides agreed that the Laotian envoy, who is the 
UN Supreme Commissary, will come to Minsk and receive data on 
this complex problem, which is persistently plaguing us. The 
envoy will then visit the Baltic states to contribute to 
resolving the problem of national minorities, including 
Belarusians, in Latvia and Estonia. [passage omitted] 
  UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali has left for 
Geneva. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-15329 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov068_g_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-068 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Government Hands Over Humanitarian Aid </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Government Hands Over Humanitarian Aid </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704210794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1950 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704210794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by BELINFORM-TASS correspondent Lidiya Peresypkina] </F>
  [Text] Minsk 7 April, TASS -- A ceremony of handing over 
the equipment of the American moth balled military hospital 
worth over 8 million U.S. dollars to Belarus was held at the 9th 
Clinical Hospital in Minsk on Thursday. 
  The Belarusian public learned about this valuable present 
from the U.S. Government to the republic which had badly 
suffered from the accident at the Chernobyl nuclear power 
station, during U.S. President Bill Clinton's recent visit to 
Minsk. The President's wife, Hillary Clinton, visited then the 
4th Children's Clinical Hospital in the Belarussian capital, met 
with medical workers and organizers of public health and 
familiarized herself with the needs of Belarussian medical 
institutions. That is why the equipment packed in 130 
containers, 20 tons each, includes unique surgical furniture and 
roentgen apparatuses, refrigerators and microscopes, and special 
beds for patients. Apart from the 9th clinic, this equipment 
will be received by the 4th Children's Clinic, well known to the 
U.S. side, the Research Institute of Radiation Medicine and the 
Minsk first-aid hospital. 
  The U.S. Government has been rendering humanitarian aid to 
Belarus on a regular basis lately which is estimated at over 100 
million U.S. dollars. 
  Still, the handing over of this considerable humanitarian 
cargo is a very important fact for many reasons. First, medical 
workers of the Republic received valuable and unique equipment 
which this country cannot afford to buy. Second, the process of 
the delivery of this humanitarian cargo became a bridge of 
friendship between the two armies as from both sides the cargo 
was dispatched and received by people in a military uniform. In 
addition, during the transportation of the cargo help was 
rendered by marines from the United Kingdom of Great Britain and 
North Ireland. 
  Some 30 young U.S. servicemen headed by Major-General of the 
Medical Service Michael Scotty, arrived in Belarus and now 
together with their Belarusian colleagues are not only receiving 
the cargo but also training Belarusian medical workers to handle 
the equipment unfamiliar to them. 
  During the ceremony of presenting the humanitarian aid 
General Michael Scotty noted that for the first time during his 
30 years of service he was handing over the Army property not 
for military but for peaceful purposes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-15330 </DOCNO>
