<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kebich Launches Presidential Bid With Attacks on Rivals </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kebich Launches Presidential Bid With Attacks on Rivals </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK0704113094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 7 Apr 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> MK0704113094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Valentin Zhdanko from Minsk under the "Belarus" </F>
rubric: "Mr. Kebich Wants To Be President. He Thinks That the 
End Justifies the Means"] 
  [Text] The number of potential candidates for the 
Republic's presidency is growing by the day, but the most 
probable rivals whose names are set to be included on the ballot 
are three: Prime Minister Vyacheslav Kebich, [former] speaker 
Stanislav Shushkevich, and Aleksandr Lukashenko, director of a 
state-owned farm in Mogilev Oblast, who heads the government 
anticorruption commission. 
  The candidates have already engaged in a struggle that 
sometimes takes on risky forms, with Mr. Kebich setting the 
tone. On the evening of 5 April, Aleksandr Lukashenko's office 
at Government House was sealed. This was done on the pretext 
that the ad hoc anticorruption commission had completed its 
mission and should be dissolved. At the same time, most 
commission members have announced that they are quitting it. 
However, there has been no Supreme Soviet decision on the 
subject. Mr. Lukashenko himself has promised to fight to the 
bitter end and is intent on staying on as commission chairman 
regardless of who its members will be. The incident of sealing 
the main corruption fighter's office was immediately described 
by Aleksandr Lukashenko's supporters as schemes by "a corrupt 
government." 
  Mr. Kebich also made a harsh attack against his other 
dangerous rival, Stanislav Shushkevich. Colonel Zametalin, the 
prime minister's press secretary, issued a statement calling the 
former speaker's candidacy "the most controversial and 
inconsistent one, prone to political flirtation." Mr. 
Shushkevich was accused by the press secretary of "demoralizing 
the Supreme Soviet by having turned it from a legislature into a 
debating society." As an example, he cited the fact that the 
parliament has been unable to pass the Constitution for two 
years. Only upon the arrival of a new speaker was the 
Fundamental Law adopted. 
  None of the candidates has a clear edge at this stage. The 
current prime minister's chances may receive a strong boost, 
however, if the money systems of Belarus and Russia are unified. 
The government is doing its utmost these days to accelerate the 
process. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-15334 </DOCNO>
