<H3> <TI>   Intelligence Service: Baltics Treated Same as Europe </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Intelligence Service: Baltics Treated Same as Europe </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0604162194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1416 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0604162194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature by diplomatic </F>
correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboynikov, Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy 
Trubetskoy and others] 
  [Text] In contrast to CIS countries against which Russia 
does not wage any intelligence operations, Russia's Intelligence 
Service treats the Baltic states as any other European 
countries, the press secretary of the Intelligence Service 
Director Tatyana Samolis declared in her interview with Interfax 
on Wednesday. 
  She voiced a supposition that the Federal 
Counterintelligence 
Service Director Sergey Stepashin, who declared at the 
scientific-practical conference in Moscow that the Eastern 
European countries as well as the former Soviet republics "make 
their intelligence activity against Russia more active," 
primarily meant the Baltic states. 
  Samolis underlined that "Russia's tactics with respect to 
the 
Baltic states will be a corresponding one in case Russia's 
interests demand this." 
  At the same time she specially noted that "if Russia does 
not 
wage intelligence operations in CIS countries it does not mean 
that it is not interested in the processes going on there." "In 
1992 eight CIS states signed an agreement prohibiting 
intelligence activity against each other. Nevertheless, Russian 
intelligence follows the situation by all available means, 
including special ones, -- said Samolis. They include 
information collection via the third countries and analysis of 
open sources. For example, we receive part of the information 
about Tajikistan from Afghanistan. Russia's leadership does not 
remain without any analysis of the processes taking place in CIS 
countries." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

