<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian-Speakers Warn of `Social Explosion' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian-Speakers Warn of `Social Explosion' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0704162694 Tallinn BNS in English 1030 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0704162694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Apr 07, BNS -- Two organizations of 
Estonia's Russian-speaking population warned the government 
yesterday of a "social explosion" if the effective regulations 
for issuing residence and work permits to non-citizens are not 
changed. 
  The Russian Representative Assembly and the Russian 
Community 
are of the opinion that the application of the aliens law, which 
met with an otherwise "positive response," by the executive 
branch of power is a "juridical trap" which deprives most of the 
non-citizens of a number of their rights. 
  The statement notes that at present only temporary residence 
and work permits for a one-year term are issued to persons who 
lived in Estonia before July 1990. The permits don't grant them 
social and economic rights promised upon adoption of the aliens 
law, the statement claims. 
  In the opinion of the Russian organizations, the problem can 
be solved only legislatively. The Russian Representative 
Assembly and the Russian Community have made their proposals for 
this to the government through the minorities' round-table 
conference. 
  The proposals include defining legally the status of persons 
who were born on the Estonian territory or arrived in the 
country before July 1, 1990, and were registered as Estonian 
residents by the authorities of the Estonian SSR; introducing a 
guarantee in the aliens law that permanent residents of Estonia 
will be issued permanent residence permits; and defining the 
exact meaning of "permanent residence and work permit," 
"temporary residence and work permit," "cadre personnel of 
foreign armed forces," and "sufficient legal income" in the 
aliens law. 
  Both Russian organizations announce that, until such 
decisions have been passed, they cannot advise non-citizens to 
apply for residence and work permits. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

