<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Liberal Democrats, Communists Block Law on Court </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Liberal Democrats, Communists Block Law on Court </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0804103494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0907 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0804103494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Aleksandrovna] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 8 TASS -- The Liberal Democratic and 
Communist parties of Russia on Friday prevented the State Duma 
from approving the Federal Constitutional bill, "On the 
Constitutional Court of the Russian Federation" in first 
reading. The bill received 247 votes "for", 51 "against", and 
another 87 deputies abstained. The bill fell 53 votes short of 
the two-thirds approval needed in the 450-member State Duma, the 
parliament's lower chamber. 
  Liberal Democratic representatives said they abstained from 
the vote because they believe the regulations concerning the 
nomination and confirmation of candidates for positions on the 
Constitutional Court need to be changed. 
  The bill, prepared in accordance with the Constitution, 
declares that candidates are to be nominated by the president 
and confirmed by the Federation Council, the upper house. The 
Liberal Democratic Party would like to see the candidates 
subject to nation-wide discussion. 
  Deputies from the Communist Party voted against the bill, 
saying that the price for their support was a series of 
important amendments. They think that the Constitutional Court 
should have the power to independently raise the most important 
issues, that the State Duma should be able to propose court 
candidates to the president, that judges should be limited to 
ten years of service on the country's highest court, and that 
all the court's current judges should be re-elected to the 
expanded Constitutional Court. 
  The Communists' demands would automatically necessitate a 
constitutional amendment, since they contradict the basic law, 
Deputy Chairman of the Duma Mikhail Mitikov pointed out. 
  The State Duma committee on legislation and judical-legal 
reform has been ordered to continue work on the bill. Committee 
Chairman Vladimir Isakov announced that there is no "tragedy" in 
the fact that the document, which has already been agreed upon 
by all the branches of power and is supported by a majority of 
the Duma deputies, will have to be refined some more. He 
expressed his assurance that the Duma would be able to reach an 
agreement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

