<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meshkov Condemns Leadership, Corrects `Mistakes' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meshkov Condemns Leadership, Corrects `Mistakes' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0704154794 Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network in 
Ukrainian 1400 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS0704154794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Crimean President Yuriy Meshkov held a news 
conference today devoted to the latest events in Crimea's 
political and economic life. He negatively commented on the 
introduction of the office of the Ukrainian president's 
representative in Crimea, describing this step as a political 
provocation aimed at hindering the second round of elections for 
the Crimean Supreme Council. Regarding presidential 
representative Valeriy Horbatov, Yuriy Meshkov said in a 
televised interview yesterday that Crimean interests are 
Horbatov's least concern, and that a honest man who cherishes 
these interests will not shake his hand. At the news 
conference, Meshkov added that the Republic of Crimea has lost 
one of its citizens. In a sharp and even offensive tone, 
Meshkov spoke of the Ukrainian leadership, which, in his 
opinion, prevents the Crimea from dealing with its economy, 
provokes confrontation, and creates tensions on the peninsula. 
The presence of military subunits saturated -- as he put it -- 
with nationalistic spirit not only does not guarantee Crimean 
security, but also threatens it. 
  Many questions from journalists concerned relations between 
Yuriy Meshkov and Crimean Deputy Prime Minister Yevhen Saburov. 
Meshkov stated that he corrected Saburov's mistakes by issuing 
another decree. Effective today, the previous low prices for 
bread are reinstated in the Crimea. The Crimean president does 
not share the concern that Saburov might be dismissed, which is 
being voiced behind the scenes. 

</TEXT>

