<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Adviser Warns Meshkov `Poses World Danger' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk Adviser Warns Meshkov `Poses World Danger' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704222394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1359 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704222394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] "Crimean President Yuriy Meshkov poses a danger to 
the world as well as Europe because his hasty actions might turn 
the Crimea into a hot spot," Nikolay Mikhalchenko, Ukrainian 
president's chief adviser on domestic issues told 
INTERFAX-Ukraine Thursday. 
  In his words, "if the situation is further destabilized in 
the Crimea, the Ukrainian authorities will do their best to have 
the Constitution of Ukraine respected and observed in the 
Crimea." 
  Mikhalchenko emphasized his absolute confidence that the new 
Ukrainian parliament will confirm the views of the previous one 
on the Crimea. 
  He said that certain people in the Crimea had for months 
been 
trying to provoke a deterioration of Russo-Ukrainian relations. 
  Mikhalchenko emphasized that Ukraine had on every occasion 
responded to specific violations of the Constitution and the 
law, "never precipitating the events. Kiev has done nothing 
that can be described as extremist or provocative." 
  He asked, "How can the Crimea be allowed to do what its 
authorities want while the Crimean president teaches contempt of 
legality to his citizens?" 

</TEXT>

