<DOCNO> FBIS4-15376 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov068_f_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-068 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kuchma Pledges To Create `Strong Center' in Parliament </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kuchma Pledges To Create `Strong Center' in Parliament </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704222094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1359 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704222094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] "I intend to create a strong center in the 
newly-elected parliament in order to oppose both the right-and 
left-oriented forces," President of the Ukrainian Union of 
Industrialists and Entrepreneurs (UUIE) and Ukraine's ex-premier 
Leonid Kuchma announced at a press conference on 6 March in Lvov. 
  During the first round of voting to the Ukrainian parliament 
Communists gained a substantial success in Eastern Ukraine and 
National Democrats and National Radicals -- in Western Ukraine. 
  The second voting in elections to the parliament will be 
held 
9-10 April. 
  In Kuchma's opinion, Ukraine "has already crossed the 
threshhold beyond which is mass industrial recession." He 
placed the responsibility for this on the government and 
National Bank. 
  As Kuchma said, he will insist "on the need for a single 
economic space without which the republics of the former USSR 
cannot survive." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

