<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nuclear Power Plant Admits Faulty Operation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nuclear Power Plant Admits Faulty Operation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0804085794 Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY in Ukrainian 5 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU0804085794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "The Zaporizhzhya Atomic Electric </F>
Power Plant [AES] Yesterday, Today, and Tomorrow"] 
  [Text] Last year, Zaporizhzhya atomic engineers alone 
produced 27,567,000 million kilowatt-hours of electric energy. 
Over the last year, the share of the AES's in Ukraine's power 
engineering rose from 29 to 33 percent. 
  However, unfortunately, alongside this, there also are other 
kinds of increase. Over 1993, at the Zaporizhzhya AES, for 
example, there were 79 cases of faulty operation of power units. 
  Among other problems, there is the shortage of funds for 
purchasing nuclear fuel in Russia. As a consequence, the fuel 
could only be purchased for three out of five units, at which 
fuel must be reloaded this year. 
  Specialists of the Zaporizhzhya AES themselves decided to 
tackle the problem of storing the used fuel directly in the 
plant's industrial area. A contract has been concluded between 
the "Zaporizhzhya AES" Production Association and the U.S. 
company "Duke Power" on constructing temporary dry-storage 
depots. Today, this is the safest and the most reliable design. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

