<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Aide Against `Compromise' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Aide Against `Compromise' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704214194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1359 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704214194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Head of the Yeltsin administration's information 
department Petr Filippov believes that the spectrum of political 
forces involved in fleshing out a civic peace pact must be 
limited. In an interview with Interfax on Thursday, he said it 
made no sense to try to involve such hardline opposition members 
as those granted amnesty recently in work over the draft. 
  "If these people say they will agree to sign pact under 
their 
own terms, there can be no question of consensus with them," 
Filippov said. "I cannot really see how it will be possible to 
sign a peace pact with a party like Barkashov's," he added. 
  The official said that "if there is a certain group of 
people 
who uphold extremist views, this does not mean that society must 
seek a compromise with them." The question is one of opening 
dialogue between the government and a civilized opposition, 
Filippov believes. 

</TEXT>

