<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Aide on Chief Prosecutor Resignation Affair </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Aide on Chief Prosecutor Resignation Affair </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704172994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1535 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704172994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anna Melnikova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 7 TASS -- "Aleksey Ilyushenko remains 
acting procurator-general of the Russian Federation, and Aleksey 
Kazannik is not Russia's chief prosecutor," Yeltsin's aide 
Georgiy Satarov told ITAR-TASS after the Federation Council 
passed a resolution defying Yeltsin's decree dismissing Kazannik 
from the post. 
  He explained that "Aleksey Kazannik is not 
procurator-general 
because his candidature was not presented to the Federation 
Council and was not endorsed in the post in the first place." 
  Commenting on today's decision of the upper chamber, Satarov 
said that "it was not a legal but a political decision. The 
Federation Council interpreted the Constitution, which amounts 
to violating it," he stressed. 
  According to Satarov, the situation reflects a conflict 
between two standards one of which is coming to replace the 
other." One was set by the president's decree 1400 appointing 
Aleksey Kazannik procurator-general, and the other is set in the 
Constitution, under which the procurator general must be 
nominated by the president and confirmed by the Federation 
Council. 
  According to Satarov, Boris Yeltsin accepted Kazannik's 
resignation to resolve the conflict of the two norms and thus 
cleared space for the new constitution." 
  Satarov thinks that this legal uncertainty, which arose in 
the wake of the Federation Council's move today "further 
complicates the struggle against crime and blocks the activity 
of the procurator's office." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

