<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kazannik Confirms Resignation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kazannik Confirms Resignation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0804064894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0630 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0804064894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 8 TASS--Alexey Kazannik, the former 
Russian prosecutor general, confirmed his resignation at a 
meeting of the Federation Council on Friday. Speaker of the 
upper chamber Vladimir Shumeyko said that this ends the dispute 
over the prosecutor general. 
  The Federation Council snubbed the Russian president on 
Thursday by reinstating Kazannik as the prosecutor general which 
it could not do as Kazannik was not nominated by Boris Yeltsin. 
According to the Constitution, it is the Federation Council 
which appoints the prosecutor, but the candidate is to be 
nominated by the president. 
  Kazannik resigned after freeing anti-Yeltsin rebels 
according 
to the Duma-proclaimed amnesty and Yeltsin accepted his 
resignation. The president then appointed Alexey Ilyushenko as 
acting prosecutor general. After the Federation Council refused 
to sack Kazannik, Georgiy Satarov, a Yeltsin's aide, said the 
decision did not mean that he would be reinstated. Ilyushenko 
would remain acting prosecutor general, according to him. Most 
observers said the decision of the upper chamber was based on 
political grounds, not on juridical ones. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

