<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Creates `Analytical Council' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Creates `Analytical Council' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0804110394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1025 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0804110394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 8 TASS -- Boris Yeltsin ruled to create 
an expert-analytical council, an analytical centre at the 
president [as received] and an information-technical centre of 
analytical research at the presidential administration in order 
"to improve the analytical and information provision of the 
Russian president and the quality of preparing the decisions of 
the president", the office of the Russian leader said on Friday. 
Marat Guriyev was appointed the head of the new 
information-technical centre. 
  The decision came one day after a scandal caused by a 
resolution of the president which mentioned Latvia among 
possible countries where Russia intends to have its military 
bases. 
  Presidential spokesman Vyacheslav Kostikov explained on 
Thursday that Latvia was mentioned in the document because of a 
"technical mistake". However, a source in the presidential 
administration told TASS the restructuring was not linked with 
the "technical mistake" and was a planned reorganisation. The 
source added that Guriyev's appointment was a promotion. 
  Yeltsin also dissolved his analytical centre for general 
policy and the analytical centre for social-economic policy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

