<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev on Zhirinovskiy, Unemployment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev on Zhirinovskiy, Unemployment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704222794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1536 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704222794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: Reports by </F>
diplomatic correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboinikov, Igor Porshnev, 
Vitaliy Trubetskoy, and others] 
  [Text] Kozyrev said that numerous politicians felt no 
responsibility for what they were doing to their country. 
"Regrettably, our numerous partners in the West fail to 
understand that some Russian politicians, notably the LDPR 
[Liberal Democratic Party of Russia] leader Vladimir 
Zhirinovskiy, are more interesting for medical than for 
political science. Western businessmen tend to abandon plans to 
invest in Russia after reading in newspapers what such politicos 
have to say. The net effect is obviously anti-Russian, not 
patriotic," he said. 
  Kozyrev was confident that Zhirinovskiy, a clownish figure, 
would not be elected anywhere again. 
  Kozyrev would like to switch the foreign policy from 
ideology 
and man-made problems inherited from the cold war to everyday 
problems of common people, above all in Russian outlying regions 
which make the core of Russia. 
  In Kozyrev's view, "the state should not harm the regions or 
obstruct their development. There is much talk of unemployment 
while roads deep inside Russia are such that one is afraid of 
riding them. Road construction is the sphere where quite a lot 
of people can be employed." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

