<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Unions, Employers, Government Sign Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trade Unions, Employers, Government Sign Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0804130794 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1000 GMT 
8 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0804130794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] An overall agreement was signed today in Moscow 
by the all-Russia trade union associations, the employers, and 
the government. The document spells out general principles for 
conducting an agreed socio-economic policy in Russia. The 
government, employers, and trade unions sign such agreements 
every year. But this time, our correspondent Andrey Zenkov 
thinks, it contains something unusual. 
  [Begin Zenkov recording] Although a trilateral agreement is 
signed every year, its fate this year gave rise to particular 
concern. And if today, before my very eyes, the agreement had 
not been signed by the labor and agriculture ministers, the 
first deputy economics and finance ministers, two deputy finance 
ministers and a whole collection of other senior officials, I 
would not have had too much faith in the reality of the 
documents myself. 
  Judge for yourselves. Paragraph two of part one envisages an 
agreed settlement and state control of energy prices and fares. 
And paragraph 22 of part three talks about clearing all the 
wage arrears for workers in state-financed sectors in the second 
quarter of this year. Fresh state subsidies worth billions can 
be seen with the naked eye, yet no trace can be detected of any 
compromise moves by the trade unions, for example. Let's say, a 
temporary renunciation of strike action. Anyway, the immediate 
future will give analysts the opportunity to assess the document 
in detail. [end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

