<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] [Correspondent P. Korovyakovskiy] Lots of secret 
things have become known in recent years. We now know about 
underground towns, about the bugs in the American Embassy, and 
even about the anti-aircraft system. Probably there is only one 
thing that we do not know much about: What is happening deep 
within the president's administration and how his, frankly 
speaking, large apparatus works and what it is doing. 
  Meanwhile, sociologists believe that it is precisely because 
there is such an information vacuum that the authorities are 
often unable to explain the logic of economic and political 
reforms to the population, and the laws, programs, and 
directives that are prepared. 
