<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chubays, Chernomyrdin on Privatization Progress </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chubays, Chernomyrdin on Privatization Progress </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704173794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1340 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704173794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Ivan Ivanov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 7 TASS -- Russian privatisation chief 
Anatoliy Chubays said that 70 per cent of trading, public 
catering and every-day service facilities have been already 
privatised in Russia. Chubays believes that by the end of the 
year this figure will reach 85-90 per cent. Also 80 per cent of 
20,000 large industrial enterprises subject to privatisation 
have changed hands, he said. 
  Speaking at a closed-door session of the Russian Government 
Presidium on Thursday, the vice-premier said that the 
privatisation voucher has already paid off. As of April 1, 1994 
105 million privatisation vouchers had been collected. That 
leaves about 45 million vouchers to be still collected. A total 
of 650 voucher investment funds have been set up in the country. 
The major result of privatisation is that joint stock companies 
and privatised enterprises remain open to foreign and domestic 
investors, Chubays said. 
  Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin noted that the Russian 
Government will not backtrack on the course of reforms, adding, 
however, that "we must be sure that we are going the right way. 
Particularly, we must make sure that privatisation does not turn 
out to be a sham." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

