<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zaveryukha: No Grain Purchase Contracts This Year </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zaveryukha: No Grain Purchase Contracts This Year </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704212694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1715 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704212694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia has not concluded a single contract to 
purchase grain from abroad since the beginning of this year, 
Russian Vice Prime Minister Aleksandr Zaveryukha told a 
conference of representatives of 55 regions who had come to a 
wholesale fair in Sochi, Krasnodar territory. Zaveryukha said 
Russia's current stocks of soft grain will last until the new 
harvest, those of fodder for 1.5 years and those of rice and 
other cereals for two years. 
  In 1993, Russia concluded contracts on the purchase of 16 Mn 
tons of grain, while its imports totalled only 11 Mn tons the 
same year. In 1992, Russia's grain purchases amounted to 26 Mn 
tons. 
  At the same time, Zaveryukha called for stricter control 
over 
the use of stocks of grain and other food staples. In his 
opinion, this is a task for a nation-wide network developed by 
the World Bank, Russian Agriculture and Food Ministry and the 
Finance Ministry which would store information about the current 
state of the stocks, prices of the products and other data. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

