<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Factories' Hard Currency Accounts To Be Taxed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Factories' Hard Currency Accounts To Be Taxed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704225094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1853 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704225094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The State Taxation Office of Russia, the Central 
Bank of Russia and the Finance Ministry have issued a ruling 
making it possible to tax and fine the hard currency accounts of 
factories and organizations if their ruble accounts have been 
exhausted. 
  Deputy head of the Taxation Office Nikolay Ivanov told the 
Financial Information Agency that as the payment crisis was 
raging in the country, numerous factories, organizations and 
commercial banks failed to pay taxes or tried to delay the 
payments by keeping their cash in hard currency accounts. 
  This step will enable the Taxation Office to collect 
significant amounts. As of April 1 various organizations owed 
the budget about 5.5 trillion rubles. 
  Ivanov emphasized that the ruling provided for very strict 
penalties for bank officers who failed to carry out the 
procedure. 
  He also said that the Finance Ministry, the Taxation Office 
and the CBR have submitted to the government proposals on 
tighter controls over bank and factory managers as far as rules 
of storing, using and transferring cash were concerned. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

