<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   1,500 Military Enterprises To Be Privatized </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    1,500 Military Enterprises To Be Privatized </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704200194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1715 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704200194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia plans to complete its program for the 
privatization of military enterprises by the end of 1994, said 
the State Committee for the Defense Industry. 
  According to a report prepared by the committee for 
parliamentary debates, more than 700 enterprises have already 
been privatized of a total of 1,500 subject to 
denationalization. "The pace of privatization in the defense 
industry is constantly increasing," the report says. While 
before 1993 it was decided to privatize 131 enterprises, by the 
beginning of this year the number trebled. Today another 640 are 
undergoing privatization, the report says. 
  It says privatization has been particularly intensive in the 
electronics, aircraft and ship-building industries. The report 
also says the State Committee for the Defense Industry is making 
serious efforts to attract capital to military enterprises. 
Thus, investment projects involving more than 170 enterprises 
are due to be carried out this year, the report says. 

</TEXT>

