<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   St Petersburg Assembly Short of Requisite Quorum </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    St Petersburg Assembly Short of Requisite Quorum </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0704151994 Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI in Russian 6 Apr 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> PM0704151994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Yuriy Kukanov under the "Regional Elections" </F>
rubric: "Half an Assembly Is Still Not an Organ"] 
  [Text] St. Petersburg -- Forty-eight hours before the 
second round of voting was held 3 April, the city court rejected 
an action brought by St. Petersburg Prosecutor's Office 
appealing against the mayor's decision to extend the 20 March 
election of a new organ of representative power by 24 hours. 
But this does not at all mean that the elections to the city 
assembly are being regarded as valid, because the Prosecutor's 
Office intends to appeal to the Russian Federation Supreme Court 
against the ruling. 
  Without waiting for the preliminary results of the 3 April 
voting, one thing can be said with certainty: The candidates 
elected to the city assembly do not include a single 
representative of the Communist Party of the Russian Federation, 
the Liberal Democratic Party of Russia, or the "Homeland" or 
"Great Russia" electoral blocs, which gathered under their 
banners orthodox Bolsheviks, Anpilov's communist workers, and 
nationalist-oriented organizations. Back on 20 March the 
politically-aware citizens of the city on the Neva confounded 
sociologists, who had predicted that the main struggle would be 
between Communist, Liberal Democrat, and "Democratic Unity of 
Petersburg" bloc candidates. The last-named got the largest 
number of candidates for deputies' seats -- 18 -- through to the 
second round. 
  Most likely only one-half of the city assembly's 50 seats 
will be occupied as a result of the repeat voting. But half an 
assembly is still not an organ of representative power because, 
according to current legislation, it can be legally constituted 
only if two-thirds, in other words 34, deputies are present. It 
is proposed to elect the missing deputies in fall. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

