<H3> <TI>   Others Comment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Others Comment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0704181494 Tallinn BNS in English 1648 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0704181494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Apr 07, BNS -- President Boris Yeltsin's 
April 5 decision clearly reflects the aggressive intentions of 
Russia's foreign policy to keep Latvia in its sphere of 
influence, the Latvian Saeima (parliament) Homeland and Freedom 
faction said. 
  The reference by Ambassador Aleksandr Rannikh to a technical 
mistake is curious from the point of view of international 
relations and only indicates of various understanding of 
political tactics by various Russian leaders, said faction head 
Maris Grinblats. It's not enough to consider that Russia has 
given up its aggressive plans. 
  Grinblats characterized the anticipated signature of the 
agreement on the Skrunda radar functioning and the status of 
military retirees in Latvia as a "political suicide." 

</TEXT>

