<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Premier Seeks Official Retraction </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Premier Seeks Official Retraction </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704220994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 2119 
GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0704220994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Kuchina] </F>
  [Text] Riga, 8 Apr -- "Spoken apologies are not enough," 
Latvian Prime Minister Valdis Birkavs said in regard to Russia's 
references to an erroneous mention of Latvia in an order by 
Boris Yeltsin on setting up bases on the territory of that 
Baltic state. "In the given situation it will not be possible to 
sign the agreements initialled and additional talks are needed," 
the head of government stressed. "But they can only take place 
after the order in question is recalled at official level." 
  Valdis Birkavs spoke on local television on Thursday 
evening. 
He arrived in the studio after cutting short his attendance at 
a meeting of the governing coalition in the Saeima, and laid out 
the position of the "Latvias Tselsh" faction, which is part of 
the coalition with the Christian Union faction. Birkavs has 
frequently stressed that a treaty on withdrawing troops from 
Latvia is necessary, but "all obscurities should be removed." 
In his words, "if a treaty is not signed, great uncertainty 
will arise given the aggressive aims of Russia expressed in the 
document signed by Mr. Yeltsin." In his opinion, "Russia has 
shown that it does not need a treaty, but for Latvia it is 
necessary." 
  Concern has been caused at the Latvian Foreign Ministry by 
the information that Russia's Foreign Ministry had not taken 
part in the drafting of the document. "If that is the case how 
are the President's orders prepared?" Maris Riekstinsh, Latvian 
Foreign Ministry state secretary asked. "We have not received 
any clarifications and have only the report that a mistake was 
made." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

