<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   }Russian Ambassador Summoned </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    }Russian Ambassador Summoned </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704151094 Vilnius Radio Vilnius Network in Lithuanian 
1400 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0704151094 </F>
<F P=104>  Vilnius Radio Vilnius Network </F>
<F P=105>  Lithuanian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Albinas Januska, Lithuanian deputy minister of 
foreign affairs, today summoned Nikolay Obertyshev, Russian 
ambassador extraordinary and plenipotentiary in Lithuania, to 
the Lithuanian Ministry of Foreign Affairs. The view of the 
Lithuanian Government on the decree of Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin was explained to the ambassador. He was told that such 
unilateral actions by Russia are unacceptable to Lithuania. 
  The attention of the ambassador was drawn during the meeting 
to the fact that the Russian stand, disseminated by the Russian 
diplomatic missions, attempting to disclaim the annexation of 
the Baltic states in 1940, has no historical or legal 
foundations. Such a stand is contrary to the Lithuanian-Russian 
agreement of 29 July 1991 on the foundations of interstate 
relations, where Russia acknowledged that in 1940 the USSR 
annexed Lithuania. 
  In discussing the return of the Lithuanian Embassy building 
in Paris, Albinas Januska expressed his concern that Russia has 
so far failed to solve this issue. 

</TEXT>

