<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Presidential Adviser Notes `Tension' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Presidential Adviser Notes `Tension' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0704182694 Tallinn BNS in English 1648 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0704182694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Apr 07, BNS -- Russia's intentions to 
create military bases in Latvia and countries of the CIS "can 
hurt the fragile agreement between Russia and Latvia on the 
Skrunda radar base," Justas Paleckis, foreign policy adviser to 
the Lithuanian president, said Thursday [7 April]. 
  Russian President Boris Yeltsin signed a decree April 5 
suggesting Foreign and Defense ministries to create bases in 
Latvia and the CIS for testing new weapons systems. 
  Paleckis said he hasn't seen the official text of the decree 
yet, but if media reports are precise enough, the Russian 
leader's decision can create tension in Baltic-Russian relations. 
  The presidential adviser said the decree contradicts 
Brazauskas' view that the Baltic coast should be free of arms in 
the future. Paleckis said the idea was mentioned in the 
Lithuanian president's speech at the United Nations last year. 
  Paleckis said military bases in foreign countries is an 
international practice, "but everything depends on historic 
circumstances and agreement between states, while the historic 
circumstances for Russia's military return to the Baltic states 
are unfavorable in this case." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

