<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Presidents Release Statement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Presidents Release Statement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0804105394 Vilnius Radio Vilnius Network in Lithuanian 
0900 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0804105394 </F>
<F P=104>  Vilnius Radio Vilnius Network </F>
<F P=105>  Lithuanian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The presidents of Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania have 
urged the Russian president, Boris Yeltsin, to state personally 
and publicly that Latvia's inclusion into the countries where 
Russia intends to establish military bases is a mistake, and to 
confirm his previous obligations to withdraw speedily and 
completely the army from Estonia and Latvia. 
  The Baltic presidents also appeal to the international 
community not to stand aside at a time when Russia is hardening 
its policy toward these states. 
  The statement by the Baltic presidents was prepared 
yesterday 
and made public this morning. The three presidents welcome 
reports from Russia that the leaders of that country's 
government acknowledged that a mistake was made in the Boris 
Yeltsin edict of 5 April by including Latvia among the countries 
where Moscow intends to establish military bases. In welcoming 
this news, we notice with concern the consequences of such 
incidents to our countries, our relations with the Russian 
Federation and, on the whole, to the possibilities of all 
countries to work with Moscow's government, the document states. 
  The presidents note that such actions, such as the 5 April 
edict and the Moscow decision on the same day at the 
negotiations with Estonia and Latvia to repudiate matters 
already agreed upon have consequences which reach much further 
than the negotiations between our countries and Russia. 
  Such actions obviously intimidate our nations and, in 
addition, they increase tension in Europe, raising the question 
of the reliability of the Russian Government as a partner in 
negotiations. The Baltic countries have always negotiated with 
the Russian Federation benevolently, and will continue to do so. 
In addition, our governments will do everything in their power 
to reduce the consequences of these ill-fated incidents. But 
our efforts have obvious limits, and therefore we apply to all 
interested countries to help us in our efforts, the statement by 
the Estonian, Latvian and Lithuanian presidents notes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

