<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on Decree, Problems </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Comments on Decree, Problems </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704190894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1715 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704190894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Dialog between Lithuania and Russia has been 
virtually suspended, Latvian [as received] Prime Minister 
Adolfas Slezevicius said at a press conference in Vilnius on 
Thursday. 
  In the words of the prime minister, Russia "is conducting an 
aggressive economic policy in relation to the Baltic states." 
The regulation of export and import introduced in the Russian 
Federation on March 15 is "bluntly discriminating", Slezevicius 
said. 
  The Lithuanian premier also said that he had a meeting with 
the head of the Kaliningrad regional administration Yuriy 
Matochkin who in the near future is scheduled to meet with 
Chernomyrdin. Slezevicius asked him to inform the Russian 
premier about Lithuania's position. Its essence is that "if 
Russia has no intention of changing its decision and continues 
the policy aimed at reducing imports, Lithuania will have 
nothing to do but to resort to adequate measures in relation to 
the Kaliningrad region." 
  The Lithuanian premier also noted that Russia is not 
repaying 
its debt for the transit of electricity. "We would not like to 
resort to limiting this transit," Slezevicius said. 
  According to the premier, Lithuanian President Algirdas 
Brazauskas sent a letter to Russian President Boris Yeltsin 
about the problems in relations between the two states. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

