<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Details; Letter to Yeltsin </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Details; Letter to Yeltsin </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704140094 Vilnius Radio Vilnius Network in Lithuanian 
1300 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0704140094 </F>
<F P=104>  Vilnius Radio Vilnius Network </F>
<F P=105>  Lithuanian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Lithuanian-Russian dialogue has come to a halt, 
but Lithuania is striving for it -- and above all the contacts 
between the presidents of the two countries -- to be normal. 
This was stated by Prime Minister Adolfas Slezevicius at a news 
conference today. 
  The prime minister announced that President Algirdas 
Brazauskas yesterday signed a letter to Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin, describing all problems of cooperation. 
Lithuanian-Russian relations have been also discussed at a 
meeting of the foreign policy coordination council chaired by 
the president. 
  Slezevicius also said that his letters and attempts to talk 
to Russian Prime minister Chernomyrdin remain without response. 
As is known, Lithuania is inviting Russia to confirm the note 
on the coming into force of the treaty on the most favorable 
trade regime. The treaty was signed last November in Vilnius, 
but Russia has so far not ratified it. 
  The head of the Lithuanian Government also told the news 
conference that Russia is conducting an aggressive policy toward 
the Baltic states. It was also said at the news conference that 
if Russia does not change its attitude, Lithuania will take the 
same measures as regards the Kaliningrad region. 

</TEXT>

