<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foul Play Suspected in Ship's Sinking </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foul Play Suspected in Ship's Sinking </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0704162894 Tallinn BNS in English 1030 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0704162894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Apr 07, BNS - The Lithuanian freighter 
Elatma sank in the North sea under "very suspicious 
circumstances," the ship's captain told Kestutis Miniotas, 
president of the Vortika company that owned the ship, the 
Vilnius-based LIETUVOS AIDAS newspaper said. 
  As previously reported, Elatma sank early Monday [4 April] 
some 80 kilometers off the Dutch coast. All 11 crew were 
rescued by a Belgian navy helicopter. The freighter was 
transporting more than 1,300 tons of ammonium nitrate to France. 
  Miniotas quoted the ship's captain as saying that Elatma 
couldn't have started to take on water because of weather 
conditions or through technical reasons. The captain said the 
ship's hull looked as if an explosion took place inside it. 
  Miniotas said the ship's hull was in good shape and was 
supposed to keep the freighter on float even if water penetrated 
one of its sections. Elatma also had very modern navigation 
equipment, he said. 
  The company set up a special commission to investigate the 
accident and to assess the damage. 
  Elatma, 103 meters long and 12.2 meters wide, now lies 
around 
30 meters deep in a zone where international navigation is very 
intensive. The ship may have to be raised together with the 
freight. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

