<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Says Base Proposal `Surprise' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Says Base Proposal `Surprise' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704165194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1230 
GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0704165194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Vladimir Taranov and </F>
Boris Krivoshey] 
  [Text] Moscow, 7 April -- The appearance of the document on 
setting up Russian military bases in CIS countries and Latvia 
has come as a surprise to the Russian Foreign Ministry. The 
Russian Foreign Ministry did not take part in agreeing the 
document. Grigoriy Karasin, director of the press and 
information directorate of the Russian Foreign Ministry said 
this at a briefing today. 
  It is necessary to study the contents of the document, he 
said, and then we will give a really qualified assessment of its 
contents through diplomatic channels. The Russian diplomat did 
not rule out that explanations would possibly be provided in a 
different form. 
  Karasin stressed that he was against attaching unnecessary 
sensationalism to the matter. It should be sorted out, we 
should look at the document, at its wording, and who presented 
it, and after that we will promulgate our official point of 
view, he said. 
  According to him, the Russian ambassador in Riga was invited 
to the Latvian Foreign Ministry where he had talks on the 
matter. Military aspects of bilateral relations between Russia 
and Latvia were resolved and are reflected in relevant 
agreements initialed by the two countries. We confirm once 
again, the Russian diplomat said, that we adhere to the 
agreements. We regard Skrunde as a facility and not a military 
base, so there cannot be questions here. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

