<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev: Russia Not Interested in Baltic Bases </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev: Russia Not Interested in Baltic Bases </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704203794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1715 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704203794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] At a press conference at the end of his talks with 
Swedish foreign minister Margareta af Ugglas in Pskov, Andrey 
Kozyrev declared that Russia was not interested in having 
military bases in Latvia, Lithuania or Estonia and that "no 
document to this end exists." 
  Kozyrev called for "Latvia signing as soon as possible a 
package of agreements with Russia so that bilateral relations 
could be significantly improved and Russian troops pulled out of 
that republic by August 31." He added, "we also expect Estonia 
which has serious problems with Russia to move towards the 
signing of agreements. The ball is now in the Estonians' court." 
  He said that Russia "would like to resolve the 
Russo-Estonian 
border issue through cooperation but we have had no positive 
signals from the Estonian authorities. 
  The Swedish foreign minister emphasized her country's view 
that the Russian troops had to be pulled out soon and completely 
from the Baltic countries. "We also welcome Russia's desire to 
have appropriate agreements with the Baltic countries. I hope 
that such agreements will be reached with both Latvia and 
Estonia. What is important is that it happens before August 31 
which should become the final deadline for withdrawal of Russian 
troops." 
  In her words, Sweden was prepared to help Russia with 
housing 
for the servicemen leaving the Baltic countries but would like 
specific agreements on troop withdrawal come first. 

</TEXT>

