<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Diplomat on Text, Signing of Yeltsin CIS Bases Order </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK0804070094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 8 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> MK0804070094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Vladimir Abarinov report in the "Scandal" column: </F>
"Yeltsin's Order on Military Bases in Latvia Does Not Exist. 
Andrey Kozyrev: `We Are Being Tested for Firmness'"] 
  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] A highly placed Russian 
diplomat told SEGODNYA that the Foreign Affairs Ministry did not 
learn about the existence of the document on the Russian bases 
until the Russian ambassador in Riga was summoned to the Latvian 
Foreign Ministry for explanation. The copy of the paper in 
possession of the Russian delegation has been received from the 
Latvian Embassy in Moscow and has all the requisites except for 
Yeltsin's signature. The text says: "Agree with the proposal by 
the Russian Defense Ministry on creating on the territories of 
the CIS member states and the Latvian Republic of military bases 
of the Russian Federation Armed Forces to ensure the security of 
the Russian Federation and said states and also to test new arms 
and military equipment. The Russian Foreign Ministry, jointly 
with the Russian Defense Ministry and other Russian Federation 
departments concerned, are to hold talks on this question with 
the CIS member states and the Latvian Republic and to formalize 
the accords reached by corresponding documents." The paper, 
which, in the expression of a Russian diplomat, was "slipped in 
for signing" to the president, bears number 175-RP and is dated 
5 April. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

