<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Ministry Statement on Latvia Military Bases </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Ministry Statement on Latvia Military Bases </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704152294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1330 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704152294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow April 7 TASS -- ITAR-TASS received the 
following statement released by the Russian Defence Ministry on 
Thursday: 
  "In connection with the publication in the mass media of 
Order no.174-RP of April 5, 1994 of the president of the Russian 
Federation on Russian military bases on the territory of former 
Soviet republics, the Ministry of Defence of the Russian 
Federation considers it necessary to make the following 
statement. 
  "The Ministry of Defence of the Russian Federation has never 
planned and is not planning to establish any military bases on 
the territory of Latvia, nor test there new weapons and military 
hardware. The document prepared by the Ministry of Defence 
together with the Ministry of Foreign Affairs mentioned the 
establishment, on the basis of military units of the Russian 
Armed Forces stationed on the territory of former Soviet 
republics, of Russian military bases and facilities in the 
interests of ensuring the security of the Russian Federation and 
those states. It meant not the establishment of a military 
base, but the missile attack warning station in Skrunda, the 
negotiations on which are still underway with the Latvian side. 
The presidential order instructs the Ministry of Foreign 
Affairs, the Defence Ministry of Russia and other concerned 
ministries and departments to continue the negotiation process 
with the CIS member-states and Latvia on this matter." 

</TEXT>

