<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Calls Estonian Territorial Claims `Unfounded' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev Calls Estonian Territorial Claims `Unfounded' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704190994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1827 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704190994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS special correspondents Boris Vlasov and </F>
Dmitriy Gorokhov] 
  [Text] Pskov 7 April, TASS -- At a final stage of his stay 
in Pskov, Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev visited on 
Thursday the "Kunichna Gora" check point on the Russian-Estonian 
border. 
  Public representatives from the frontier town of Pechory 
handed over to him an address in which they expressed an alarm 
in connection with Estonia's territorial claims on this ancient 
Russian locality and called the leadership to strengthen and 
improve conditions on the border. 
  Andrey Kozyrev called the territorial claims of Tallinn 
unfounded and stressed that Estonia, just as Russia, were 
recognized within the existing borders. Moscow, the foreign 
minister noted, is in the know about these problems and is 
closely watching them. It is necessary to strengthen the 
border, but at the same time there is no need to make it 
"impenetrable." Here, on the spot, Andrey Kozyrev said, an 
optimal regime should be determined and a formula found which 
will suit both sides. 
  The problems of the strengthening of the border and the 
troops withdrawal are exclusively issues of bilateral relations, 
but we are interested that these problems are known and 
understood by our neighbors in the region, the Russian foreign 
minister pointed out. 
  At the same time, Andrey Kozyrev noted, there are also 
problems of the rights of the Russian speaking population in 
Estonia. These issues are not exclusively the subject of the 
Russo-Estonian dispute. After all, there is international law 
and all-European norms which must be observed. We are raising 
this issue very insistently, the Russian foreign minister 
emphasised. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

