<H3> <TI>   Official Denies Aid Used To Pressure Armenia, U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Denies Aid Used To Pressure Armenia, U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704190194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1620 
GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0704190194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Vladimir </F>
Taranov and Boris Krivoshey] 
  [Text] Moscow, 7 Apr -- The Russian State Customs Committee 
has exempted from duty deliveries of 2,000 tonnes of seed grain 
purchased with U.S. government funds and being sent from Russia 
to Armenia. By forgoing customs duties to the value of 
$750,000, Russia has thus participated in a joint humanitarian 
act with the United States. This was stated at a briefing today 
by Grigoriy Karasin, director of the press and information 
department of the Russian Foreign Ministry. 
  The Russian diplomat noted that there is some perplexity 
over 
claims by some mass media analysts that Russia intends to 
prevent the passage to Armenia of humanitarian grain in order to 
put political pressure on Yerevan and Washington. 

</TEXT>

