<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Says Srebrenica `Formula' May Work in Goradze </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Says Srebrenica `Formula' May Work in Goradze </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704222694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1536 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704222694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature by diplomatic </F>
correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboynikov, Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy 
Trubetskoy and others] 
  [Text] Russia's Foreign Ministry has closely followed the 
development of events in and around Gorazde, where clashes 
between Bosnian Serbs and Muslims flared up once again, a 
high-ranking Russian diplomat told Interfax on Thursday. 
  According to him, Bosnian Serbs reacted to Muslim acts of 
provocation in the area of Gorazde "inadequately." "The Serbs 
made a four-kilometer incursion from the disengagement line, and 
invaded several villages, whose Muslim population took shelter 
in the city of Gorazde which is controlled by Muslim units," the 
diplomat said. 
  As he said, the situation is aggravated by the circumstance 
that in Gorazde the Muslims are holding about 50 Serb prisoners 
of war, whom the field commanders of Bosnian Serbs are seeking 
to free at any cost. 
  On Friday, the official from Russia's Foreign Ministry said, 
high-ranking representatives of Bosnian Serbs and Muslims are to 
meet in Sarajevo's airport to discuss the possible ways to reach 
a settlement in Bosnia-Herzegovina as a whole, and in Gorazde in 
particular. 
  According to Interfax's interviewee, the formula that helped 
to ease tensions in and around another Bosnian city, Srebrenica, 
could be used in the area of Gorazde. "Stipulated in an 
agreement reached between Bonian Serbs, Muslims and the command 
of the U.N. protection forces, the formula provides for 
withdrawing the armed units of both sides from the line of 
confrontation, demilitarizing the "buffer" zone and deploying 
U.N. peace-keeping forces there," he said. 
  This week-end or early next week the special envoy of the 
Russian president, Deputy Foreign Minister Vitaliy Churkin, may 
make a trip to the Balkans, the diplomat said. "We are working 
in two directions -- Bosnia and Krajina. It's not surprising 
therefore that the program of his trip includes Zagreb and 
Belgrade," he added. 
  According to Interfax's interviewee, in Moscow on Wednesday 
Churkin conferred with one of the leaders of Bosnian Serbs, 
Momcilo Krajisnik, and discussed with him the situation that had 
emerged in the wake of the Washington agreements signed to form 
a Muslim-Croat federation in Bosnia-Herzegovina,and subsequently 
establish a confederation between it and Croatia. "The two men 
discussed the role Bosnian Serbs could play under these 
agreements. Russia wants the lawful rights of the third nation 
making up the state of Bosnia- Herzegovina -- Bosnian Serbs -- 
to be observed," he stressed. 
  Deputy Foreign Minister Vitaliy Churkin, special envoy of 
the 
Russian president, will fly to Belgrade Sunday, April 10 to meet 
with Serbia's leaders, Grigoriy Karasin, a spokesman for the 
Russian Foreign Ministry, said at a briefing in Moscow Thursday. 
  Karasin added that Churkin would meet with Croatian leaders 
in Zagreb Monday and the next day would attend talks on the 
economic issues of the settlement that would be held in the 
Russian embassy to Croatia. 
  Karasin did not rule out the possibility that Churkin would 
also visit Sarajevo. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

