<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Backs South African Law Enforcement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia Backs South African Law Enforcement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0804103094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0908 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0804103094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Denis Perkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 8 TASS -- "Russia backs the recent 
steps of the South African Government to enforce law and order. 
But these measures may prove insufficient without a long-term 
political agreement," a representative of the Russian Foreign 
Ministry stated at the ministry's press centre here today. 
  The developments in the Republic of South Africa are now in 
the focus of world public opinion: less than three weeks are 
left before the first universal parliamentary elections in the 
country. "All the world regards this event as a turning point in 
the history of South Africa, as a landmark after which the 
country will become a full- fledged member of the community of 
democratic states," the representative noted. 
  "In the meantime, the election campaign has brought the 
situation to a head in several parts of South Africa," the 
diplomat stated. "The political forces that are unable to win 
popularity among the electorate are becoming increasingly 
aggressive. They intend to boycott the elections and to prevent 
normal voting on the territories under their control," he added. 
The diplomat believes that "such a tactic actually leads to a 
break-up of the Republic of South Africa and threatens the 
society by an open armed confrontation frought with 
unpredictible consequences for the country an the entire region". 
  The representative of the Russian Foreign Ministry expressed 
the hope that the meeting among leaders of the conflicting 
sides, scheduled for saturday, would be constructive. The 
Russian Foreign Ministry expects "the meeting to adopt a firm 
commitment of all its participants to contribute by every means 
at their disposal to the free expression of the will of the 
South African electors on the entire territory of the country". 

</TEXT>

