<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Birkavs: Yeltsin `Order' Prevents Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Birkavs: Yeltsin `Order' Prevents Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704125894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1048 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704125894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Latvian Prime Minister Valdis Birkavs declared that 
Russian President Boris Yeltsin's order on creation of military 
bases on the territory of CIS states and Latvia makes conclusion 
of the Russian-Latvian agreement on troop withdrawal impossible. 
Birkavs declared this at a briefing staged after a special 
sitting of the Latvian Cabinet of Ministers on Wednesday in Riga 
which considered this order issued by Yeltsin. 
  As it was reported earlier a package of interstate 
agreements 
determining the date for troop withdrawal from Latvia, namely 
August 31, 1994 and several additional provisions, including the 
one concerning Russia holding on to the early-warning radar in 
Skrunda for 5.5 years, is being prepared now to be signed by 
Latvian and Russian presidents. At the briefing, Birkavs 
pointed out that the initialled agreements do not stipulate that 
this site would have the status of a military base. 
  The official statement of the Latvian Cabinet says that "the 
Latvian government has never agreed and will never agree to 
create Russian military bases on Latvian territory and to test 
new armaments and military equipment on its territory, it also 
rules out the possibility of any negotiations on these issues." 
  Birkavs added that the order of the Russian president 
appeared "under the influence of Russia's conservative circles 
whose goals coincide with the interests of Latvia's national 
radical circles -- to prevent conclusion of the Russian-Latvian 
treaty." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-15502 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov068_u_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-068 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Envoy Gives Official Apology </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Envoy Gives Official Apology </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704214594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1359 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704214594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russian Ambassador in Latvia Aleksandr Rannikh 
extended in Riga Thursday Moscow's official apologies due to the 
"misunderstanding" around President Yeltsin's order to create 
military bases outside the Russian Federation. 
  Earlier the news media said that by his order Yeltsin backed 
the initiative by the Russian Defense Ministry on the creation 
of military bases in the CIS countries and Latvia. 
  Addressing on the same day a briefing in Riga, the Russian 
Ambassador admitted that there was "a technical mistake" which 
was detrimental to the Russian-Latvian relations and made 
difficult the political dialogue. 
  Rannikh said that he had doubt about the origin of the 
document. He said that the Russian Embassy in Riga did not 
receive the official report from Moscow that the document was 
signed and was in force. 
  He believes that Latvia's negative reaction to the document 
was caused by the tense situation caused by preparations being 
under way for the signing of the Latvian-Russian agreements on 
the Russian troop pull-out. 
  Rannikh also confirmed that all problems associated with the 
pull-out and the conditions of the temporary deployment and 
status of the radar station in Skrunda were solved and the 
documents were initialed by the chief negotiators of the two 
countries on March 15. 
  According to the agreement, the Russian radar in Skrunda is 
a 
Russian military facility which is under the civilian control 
and cannot be regarded as a military base. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-15503 </DOCNO>
