<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Plan for Army Bases Rejected </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Plan for Army Bases Rejected </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1004143994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1322 GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1004143994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moldovan Deputy Defense Minister Brigadier General 
Tudor Dabija told INTERFAX that Russia would never be allowed to 
have army bases in Moldova. In Dabija's view, Yeltsin's decision 
to create army bases in Commonwealth republics was out of 
keeping with the Moldovan military doctrine. 
  The Moldovan and Russian military could negotiate only one 
issue, Dabija said, the full withdrawal of Russia's 14th Army 
from Moldovan soil. 
  On 7 April, however, the eighth round of Russian-Moldovan 
negotiations was held in Kishinev [Chisinau]. A draft agreement 
was initialled on the legal status and reciprocal legal aid in 
cases related to the temporary presence of Russian Army units on 
Moldovan territory. 
  The Moldovan and Russian delegations signed a few other 
documents to decide how they would schedule Russian troop 
withdrawal and the removal of Russian army property from Moldova. 
  They failed to agree on deadlines for the Russian troop 
withdrawal, but agreed to meet again in May. 

</TEXT>

