<F P=100> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nazarbayev Concerned Over Russian Population Leaving </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nazarbayev Concerned Over Russian Population Leaving </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0804221294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1213 
GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0804221294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Vasiliy Golovnin] </F>
  [Text] Tokyo, 8 Apr -- Kazakhstan President Nursultan 
Nazarbayev today said he was most concerned that there was a 
danger that the Russian population might leave the country. 
  Replying to questions at a news conference in Tokyo, he said 
Kazakhstan does not have a refugees' problem yet. However, 
Nazarbayev said, "collapse of empires never goes quietly," and 
people are concerned since they can see bloodshed in Tajikistan 
and the Caucasus. Politicians, he said, should have foreseen 
this when they were signing the Belovezhskaya Pushcha agreement 
and when "against our will, the ruble zone was being destroyed." 
  An economic crisis can be observed throughout the former 
USSR 
at present, the quality of life worsens, and on the eve of the 
elections on 12 December many politicians had nothing better to 
do than "to use the Russian theme since there was nothing else 
they could talk about." However, concern for common people and 
politicizing are different matters, the president stressed. 
  The Russian-speaking population in Kazakhstan enjoys all the 
rights and even have opportunities not available in other 
countries on the territory of the former USSR. "Russians, 
Germans, and Ukrainians are our citizens, citizens of 
Kazakhstan, and I know it will be worse for them if they leave," 
Nazarbayev said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

