<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Ready To Lift Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia Ready To Lift Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0804201194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1742 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0804201194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia is ready to initiate the lifting of 
international sanctions against former Yugoslavia after a 
settlement in Bosnia and Herzegovina is signed, Political 
Advisor of the Russian Foreign Minister, Galina Sidorova told 
Interfax. Sidorova said Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev 
had met Chairman of the parliament of the United Republic of 
Yugoslavia, Radoman Bozovic, today in Moscow and had made 
Moscow's position known. "The sanctions were imposed due to the 
specific situation in Bosnia and Herzegovina. As the situation 
changes, the need for sanctions disappears," Sidorova said. 
  Sidorova suggested that this new opportunity must be used to 
settle the conflict in ex-Yugoslavia. She believes that the 
Serbs should participate in the agreement recently signed by 
Bosnian Moslems and Croats. "Russia will agree with any 
decision acceptable for all Bosnian parties. However, it is 
obvious that no settlement in Bosnia and Herzegovina will work 
without the participation of the Serbs." She spoke for an 
urgent agreement on a cease-fire between Bosnian Serbs and 
Moslems at the talks begun today in Sarajevo. "The sooner it 
happens, the more chances there will be for the success of the 
political dialogue," Sidorova stressed. 
  Bozovic emphasized the important role of the Russian 
diplomacy on Balkans. He said the recent positive changes were 
due to Russia's activities. Bozovic stressed that he had met 
many Russian parliamentarians representing different political 
blocs and factions. Practically all of them spoke for lifting 
sanctions against Belgrade. These sanctions are 
counter-productive and can only do harm, Bozovic said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

