<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Ignored Russian Warnings </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs Ignored Russian Warnings </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1104121494 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1000 GMT 
11 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1104121494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by RIA-Novosti correspondent Sergey Gryzunov] </F>
  [Excerpts] [Passage omitted] We have learned from 
well-informed diplomatic sources that Russia repeatedly warned 
the Bosnian Serb leadership about the danger of stepping up 
their activities in eastern Bosnia. The last of these warnings 
was made just a few hours before the air strike. In response, 
the Russian embassy in Belgrade received firm promises that 
there would be no aggravation of the situation. But literally a 
few hours later Serb detachments mounted an offensive on Gorazde 
and occupied its southern part. As a result, the airplanes were 
forced to intervene after the lives of UN observers came under 
threat. [passage omitted] 
  After Russian diplomacy averted the bombing of Serb 
positions 
in Sarajevo, a dangerous confidence in their own impunity 
manifested itself among the Bosnian Serb leaders, generals, and 
soldiers. The withdrawal of heavy weapons was presented by 
local propaganda as a Serb victory, and the fact that NATO did 
not mount air strikes was seen as a sign of weakness and 
hesitation. But now the Rubicon has been crossed. A 
fundamentally new situation has arisen, in which the Russian 
president's special envoy Vitaliy Churkin will have to use all 
his influence and skill to continue his peace-brokering mission 
and the talks. 
  He has now begun a meeting with Serb President Slobodan 
Milosevic, during which Moscow's views on what happened in 
eastern Bosnia will probably be set forth. 

</TEXT>

