<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commission To Investigate Edict `Error' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commission To Investigate Edict `Error' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0904100294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0950 
GMT 9 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0904100294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Anna Melnikova, ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 9 April -- "The technical error that 
appeared in the Russian president's instruction of 5 April will 
undoubtedly be subject to serious investigation within the 
presidential structures responsible for preparation of this 
document," Sergey Kravchenko, deputy head of the Russian 
president's administration, stated today in the Kremlin in an 
exclusive interview with the ITAR-TASS correspondent. 
  He explained that instead of the words "military 
installation," which can be understood as a technical facility, 
a term "military base" has crept in, which radically changes the 
meaning of the document. 
  Sergey Kravchenko said that "a special commission for 
investigation into the circumstances surrounding this case will 
be set up in the next few days." In his view, it can be set up 
"by the president himself or the head of his administration." 
The deputy head of the Russian president's administration did 
not rule out the possibility of "this being not just a technical 
mistake but a political action aimed at disrupting the meeting 
between the Russian and Latvian heads of state." 

</TEXT>

