Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia To Sell Cryogenic Rocket Boosters To India </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia To Sell Cryogenic Rocket Boosters To India </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0904133394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1243 GMT 9 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0904133394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia has been meeting its commitments on the 
supplies of cryogenic rocket boosters to India. The deal, whose 
terms in line with the Missile Technology Control Regime, MTCR, 
were made public at the end of last year, has been officially 
endorsed by the Russian cabinet, a Vice-Chairman of Glavkosmos, 
Russia's major space research establishment, has said in an 
interview with Interfax. 
  In line with new terms, Russia is to deliver at least four 
cryogenic boosters to India for its SLV-3 rockets. This is 
twice more than envisaged by the contract signed by Glavkosmos 
in 1991. Lifted up by a Russian booster, SLV-3 will be able to 
put loads in orbit about 36,000 kilometers above the earth. 
  As the General Director of Russia's Space Agency Yuriy 
Koptev 
has told Interfax, supplies of ready-made cryogenic blocks are 
within MTCR, which Russia wished to join by signing a memorandum 
of intent in Washington on September 2, 1993. 
  In Koptev's words, two additional blocks will be shipped to 
India to compensate for Russia's failure to meet the initial 
commitments, concerning the supply of technologies in bypass of 
MTCR. 
  Koptev declared that Russia had kept virtually intact the 
volume of financing, totalling $300 million, envisaged by the 
contract. India is to get the first booster next year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-15566 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov069_a_94033" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-069 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   MiG Maintenance Center Planned </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MiG Maintenance Center Planned </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1104105394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0931 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1104105394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Aleksey Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] New Delhi April 11 TASS -- Russia plans to begin 
before the end of this year the building of a maintenance centre 
in India to service Soviet and Russian-made airplanes of the MiG 
series that are being used by the Indian armed forces. 
  The Indian EXPRESS newspaper reported, citing sources in the 
Indian Defence Ministry, that the centre will be built jointly 
by the Hindustan Aeronautics Limited (HAL) and the Moscow 
Aircraft-Producing Association (MAPO) as a pilot project in the 
country, which will provide services to other countries whose 
armed forces use the MiG planes, from the MiG-21 to the MiG-29, 
primarily in Southeast Asia. 
  Commenting on this report at a request from ITAR-TASS, an 
informed Russian source in New Delhi, speaking on condition of 
anonymity, confirmed that an agreement on the building of a 
maintenance centre has been signed between HAL and MAPO. The 
realisation of this agreement will be a subject of negotiations 
between a high-ranking delegation from the Ministry of the 
Aircraft Industry of the Russian Federation, which is due to 
arrive in India in the middle of April, and Indian authorities. 
  According to the same source, Indian press reports about the 
interests shown in the construction of the enterprise by the 
airforces of Malaysia, Vietnam and some Arab countries are 
premature. According to the source, they are rather interested 
in developing their own potential in this direction. 
  Nonetheless, undoubtedly, the idea of creating a maintenance 
centre marks not only a new step in the development of 
military-technical cooperation between Moscow and New Delhi, but 
will reduce the acute shortage of spare parts which the Indian 
airforce needs badly. The press blames the shortage on Russia 
which is not quite fair, according to Sergey Anishchenko, the 
local representative of the Russian state company 
Rosvooruzheniye (Russian Armaments). 
  "Despite numerous claims, it is not understandable why the 
Indian side delays the consideration and signing of contractual 
documents with Russia," Anishchenko said in an interview with 
ITAR-TASS. "In some cases the procrastination lasted up to one 
year. Sometimes when signing contracts our partners 
unilaterally annul up to 30-40 per cent of their own official 
bids". 
  Along with this Sergey Anishchenko expressed the hope that 
Rosvooruzheniye remains a highly qualified partner capable of 
solving adequately and promptly all problems in the interests of 
strengthening the Indian armed forces. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-15567 </DOCNO>
