<H3> <TI>   Armenia Unconcerned by Russian Military Presence </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Armenia Unconcerned by Russian Military Presence </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1004145794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1322 GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1004145794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The chairman off the Defense and Internal Affairs 
commission of the Armenian parliament Ghevork Bagdasaryan told 
an Interfax reporter that Armenia saw no reason for worry about 
Russian military presence because, in line with a bilateral 
treaty of 1992, a Russian Army Group, with headquarters in 
Yerevan, had already been deployed in the republic. According 
to Bagdasaryan, Armenia's borders with Iran and Turkey were 
controlled exclusively by Russian troops. 
  The treaty of 1992 was ratified by Moscow in 1993 but 
remains 
to be ratified by the Armenian parliament. A number of Armenian 
legislators would like to rewrite some parts off that document. 
They raise objections to the articles on preferential treatment 
for Russian servicemen and the creation of troop deployment 
areas in their republic. 

</TEXT>

