<H3> <TI>   Official Hopes Abkhazia Accord Will Be Honored </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Hopes Abkhazia Accord Will Be Honored </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0804203994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1906 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0804203994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Aleksandr Kavsadze, who chairs the Georgian 
parliament's Ethnic Relations and Human Rights Committee, 
expressed the hope that the Moscow agreements of April 4 on 
political settlement in Abkhazia and return of the refugees 
would be honored. 
  He told journalists in Tbilisi Friday, however, that 
unexpected events might take place if the security guarantees 
for the refugees were full implemented. 
  Kavsadze said that this agreement, like the earlier ones, 
could be wrecked but emphasized the need "to try to succeed 
jointly. You don't stop when you go in darkness, torch in hand, 
just because the torch may go out." 
  The Georgian parliament's Deputy Chairman Vakhtang 
Rcheulishvili said that future documents on Abkhazia had to be a 
detailed blueprint for the political structure of the autonomous 
republic. He called for equal rights to be given to all the 
citizens. "If the Georgian and Abkhazian populations are not 
convinced that these rights are guaranteed, there will be no 
peace," he emphasized. 
  Rcheulishvili said that those who had fought on the 
Abkhazian 
side, notably North Caucasian nationals, and seized houses 
belonging to Georgian families "are automatically regarded is 
illegal residents there." 

</TEXT>

