<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chief: Army To Have `Adequate Fighting Capacity' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chief: Army To Have `Adequate Fighting Capacity' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0804190594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1813 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0804190594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Georgia's Chief-of-General Staff General Guram 
Nikolaishvili says that regardless of all its problems that 
within two or three years, Georgia will have an army with an 
adequate fighting capacity. 
  In Friday's appearance on Georgian television Nikolaishvili 
reported good progress in the efforts to build a national army. 
The top executives of the Georgian Defense Ministry have 
drafted and approved a national military doctrine which will be 
very soon presented for endorsement to the Georgian parliament. 
  According to Nikolaishvili, the Georgian armed forces number 
up to 20,000 men. Instead of calling up reserves, the Georgian 
army practices regular army drafts. Nikolaishvili said up to 
300,000 men in the 18 to 25 age bracket had never served in the 
army. Up to ten army bases were under construction in the 
republic, he added. 
  The army's one big problem was the officers. Nikolaishvili 
explained it by financial limitations. He said a Georgian army 
officer earned an equivalent of 4,000 Russian Rubles a month. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

