<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-069 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Aide Suggests Leasing Russian Army Bases </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk Aide Suggests Leasing Russian Army Bases </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1004150894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1322 GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1004150894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia may have army bases in former Soviet 
republics only under formal lease agreements. The republics 
where it will have bases are to retain ownership of the leased 
territory and property. A worker on the staff of Ukrainian 
President Kravchuk said that in an interview with Interfax. The 
man preferred to remain unidentified. 
  The Kravchuk Administration felt the naval facilities of 
Sevastopol could be leased to Russia but must still be regarded 
as Ukrainian naval facilities on lease to Russia. If they were 
regarded as Russian property, said the unidentified 
Administration spokesman, the situation would compare to that 
around the Guantanamo base in Cuba. 
  In the meantime, chief Aleksandr Kluban of the Ukrainian 
Defense Ministry's press service told Interfax-Ukraine that the 
deployment of Russian armymen outside Russia was not Ukraine's 
headache. He said Russia had so far made no such proposition to 
his republic. 

</TEXT>

