<H3> <TI>   Officers Visit Crimea, Deny `Flexing Muscles' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Officers Visit Crimea, Deny `Flexing Muscles' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1104131894 Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY in Ukrainian 7 Apr 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU1104131894 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Is Ukraine Flexing Its Muscles?"] </F>
  [Text] On 5 April, a group of officers under the 
leadership of Hennadiy Hurin, first deputy chief of Ukraine's 
Ministry of Defense General Staff, visited the Crimea. The aim 
of the visit was to check, as scheduled, the state of affairs 
and to study problems in Ukraine's military units. On that day, 
Hennadiy Hurin visited the headquarters of Ukraine's Naval 
Forces in Sevastopol and ships of the Ukrainian Fleet. The 
group of officers also included Ukrainian presidential adviser 
for military issues Major General Volodymyr Petepko, who visited 
commander of the Black Sea Fleet Admiral E. Baltin in a naval 
hospital. 
  On the same day, Ukraine's first deputy minister of internal 
affairs Colonel General Valentyn Nedryhaylo also visited the 
Crimea. He headed a group of the ministry's officials that 
arrived in order to render assistance in the operational work on 
combating crime. 
  Both the Ministry of Defense and Ministry of Internal 
Affairs 
of Ukraine rejected the assumption by a number of mass media on 
Ukraine's alleged flexing its muscles in the absence of 
President Yu. Meshkov [who was on a visit to Cyprus at the time]. 

</TEXT>

