<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Aide: Ukraine Has Too Many Troops on Peninsula </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimean Aide: Ukraine Has Too Many Troops on Peninsula </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0804164794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1550 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0804164794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vadim Byrkin] </F>
  [Text] Simferopol April 8 TASS -- Not counting the Balkans, 
the Crimea is the most militarized place in Europe now, 
according to Valery Kuznetsov, military aide to the Crimean 
president. 
  In a conversation with ITAR-TASS on Friday, Kuznetsov 
pointed 
out that, besides the Black Sea Fleet and Ukraine's naval 
forces, around 50 thousand Ukrainian soldiers and officers are 
concentrated on the peninsula. The amount of military personnel 
located here was twice as small before the dissolution of the 
Soviet Union. 
  The presidential aide expressed his doubts in the necessity 
of maintaining such powerful military forces in the Crimea. 
Referring to operational information, Kuznetsov noted that the 
Ukrainian Defence Ministry "plans to increase its military 
presence in the Crimea". 
  The recent sudden visit of Ukraine's military leaders to the 
peninsula caused sharp indignation in the area and a sharp 
retaliatory statement from Crimean President Yuriy Meshkov. 
Similar steps by Kiev, Kuznetsov declared, are not only "a form 
of pressure, but possible training before future actions 
intended to change the situation in the Crimea". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

