<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meshkov Say He Will Not Meet Kravchuk's Envoy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meshkov Say He Will Not Meet Kravchuk's Envoy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1004162994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1515 GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1004162994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The president of the Ukrainian Autonomous Republic 
of Crimea, Yuriy Meshkov, said, "I haven't had any meetings with 
the envoy of the Ukrainian president to Ukraine, Valeriy 
Gorbatov, and hope I won't as long the Republic of Crimea 
exists." 
  Meshkov said to reporters on Sunday that the situation in 
Crimea might be destabilized before the convocation of the 
republic's legislature, elections to which are underway on 
Sunday along with those to the Ukrainian parliament. "Such 
attempts are being made by the Kiev leadership but have 
fortunately been unsuccessful so far," he said. 
  Meshkov took no part in either round of the Ukrainian 
parliamentary elections (at the first round, he took his ballot 
paper away with him and urged all other Crimean electors to do 
the same). On April 10, he only participated in the Crimean 
elections. 
  Asked about the "war of laws" between Ukraine and Crimea, he 
said, "It isn't a war of laws but Kiev's attempts to make it 
impossible for us to solve our economic problems." "It is my 
strong hope that those who take power in Ukraine will simply be 
reasonable people. That's enough for Crimea," he said. 

</TEXT>

